<DOC><DOCNO> AP880810-0263 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2339EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-USBases     08-10 0148</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Soviet-US Bases,0151</SECOND><HEAD>Soviets Will Leave Vietnam If U.S. Quits Philippines, OfficialSays</HEAD><DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Soviet official Fjodor IvanovichPotapenkno was quoted as saying Thursday that without the shadow ofa doubt, Soviet forces would leave Vietnam if the United Stateswithdrew from the Philippines.   Potapenkno, who recently returned to the Soviet Union afterbeing ambassador in Malaysia for four years, spoke in an interviewpublished in the editorial page of the daily New Straits Times.   ``The Soviet Union is reducing its military activity andpresence in the (Southeast Asia) region,'' he was quoted as saying.``There is no shadow of doubt that if United States forces leavethe Philippines _ for the United States _ Soviet forces will alsoleave Vietnam.''   The United States maintains two military bases and four minorinstallations in the Philippines and the Soviets have close ties toVietnam.</TEXT></DOC>